{"id":"math/9201228","submitter":"Gilles Pisier","authors":"Gilles Pisier","title":"A simple proof of a theorem of Jean Bourgain","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":"Banach Archive 6/3/91","categories":"math.FA","license":null,"abstract":"  We give a simple proof of Bourgain's disc algebra version of Grothendieck's\ntheorem, i.e. that every operator on the disc algebra with values in $L_1$ or\n$L_2$ is 2-absolutely summing and hence extends to an operator defined on the\nwhole of $C$. This implies Bourgain's result that $L_1/H^1$ is of cotype 2. We\nalso prove more generally that $L_r/H^r$ is of cotype 2 for $0<r< 1$.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 3 Jun 1991 16:51:48 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-09-25"}
